{
    "esm": "0.4.0",
    "metadata": {
        "name": "MaxwellianFlux",
        "description": "Continuum-regime molar flux of a gas species to a spherical particle. In the continuum limit (Kn ≪ 1) the steady-state diffusive flux is governed by Fick's law on a spherical geometry: J_c = 4πR_p D_g (c_∞ − c_s) (Seinfeld & Pandis 2006, Chapter 12, Eq. 12.12). A positive J_c indicates net uptake (c_∞ > c_s); a negative value indicates net evaporation or desorption (c_s > c_∞). Migrated from Aerosol.jl src/mass_transfer.jl `MaxwellianFlux`.",
        "tags": [
            "aerosol",
            "mass-transfer",
            "continuum-regime",
            "diffusive-flux",
            "seinfeld-pandis"
        ],
        "created": "2026-05-21T00:00:00Z",
        "authors": [
            "Aerosol.jl contributors",
            "EarthSciModels migration (esm-esr)"
        ],
        "references": [
            {
                "citation": "Seinfeld, J. H. and Pandis, S. N. (2006). Atmospheric Chemistry and Physics: From Air Pollution to Climate Change, 2nd Edition. John Wiley & Sons. Chapter 12, Eq. 12.12 (steady-state continuum-regime diffusive flux to a sphere)."
            }
        ]
    },
    "models": {
        "MaxwellianFlux": {
            "reference": {
                "citation": "Seinfeld, J. H. and Pandis, S. N. (2006) Atmospheric Chemistry and Physics, 2nd Edition, Chapter 12, Eq. 12.12 — steady-state diffusive molar flux to a spherical particle in the continuum regime. Migrated from Aerosol.jl src/mass_transfer.jl `MaxwellianFlux` (esm-esr).",
                "notes": "source_ref: Aerosol.jl@c8c640b:src/mass_transfer.jl:173\n\nUpstream `MaxwellianFlux` is an MTK `@component` with 4 parameters (R_p, D_g, c_inf, c_s) and 1 variable J_c(t) determined by one explicit algebraic equation with no time derivative — purely observed.\n\nEquation (S&P 2006, Eq. 12.12):\n  J_c = 4π R_p D_g (c_∞ − c_s)   [continuum steady-state molar flux, mol/s]\n\nThe factor 4π arises from integrating Fick's law in spherical coordinates at steady state: d/dr(r² dc/dr) = 0, giving c(r) = c_s + (c_∞ − c_s) R_p/r; the flux at the surface is J = 4π R_p² D_g (dc/dr)|_{r=R_p} = 4π R_p D_g (c_∞ − c_s). The constant 4π = 12.566370614359172 is inlined as a floating-point literal consistent with the convention used across the aerosol/mass_transfer migration family.\n\nSign convention: J_c > 0 means net absorption (c_∞ > c_s, gas condenses onto particle); J_c < 0 means net evaporation (c_s > c_∞, particle releases gas). J_c = 0 at equilibrium (c_∞ = c_s).\n\nPhysics: Valid when Kn = λ/R_p ≪ 1. For typical atmospheric aerosol (R_p ~ 0.1–10 µm at standard conditions λ ~ 65 nm), Kn spans 0.0065–0.65, so continuum corrections are often needed. The Fuchs-Sutugin (fuchs_sutugin.esm) and Dahneke (dahneke.esm) correction factors extend MaxwellianFlux to the transition and free-molecular regimes.\n\nTolerance rationale (model-level rel=1e-12): purely algebraic expression; a single multiply of four operands in float64. Round-off is ~1e-15 relative; rel=1e-12 leaves three orders of headroom and is tighter than the sibling uptake_coeff.esm (rel=1e-9) because the expression here has fewer floating-point operations."
            },
            "tolerance": {
                "rel": 1e-12
            },
            "variables": {
                "R_p": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m",
                    "default": 1.0e-7,
                    "description": "Particle radius. Default 0.1 µm is a sub-micron aerosol particle in the lower continuum regime."
                },
                "D_g": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m^2/s",
                    "default": 2.0e-5,
                    "description": "Gas-phase molecular diffusivity of the condensing/evaporating species. Default 2×10⁻⁵ m²/s is representative of small atmospheric trace gases at 298 K and 1 atm."
                },
                "c_inf": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "mol/m^3",
                    "default": 1.0e-6,
                    "description": "Bulk (far-field) gas-phase molar concentration of the species. Represents the ambient concentration far from the particle surface. Default 10⁻⁶ mol/m³ is a trace-gas level."
                },
                "c_s": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "mol/m^3",
                    "default": 0.0,
                    "description": "Molar concentration of the species at the particle surface. At equilibrium c_s equals the saturation vapor concentration (Raoult/Kelvin corrected). Default 0.0 gives maximum uptake flux."
                },
                "J_c": {
                    "type": "observed",
                    "units": "mol/s",
                    "description": "Continuum-regime molar flow rate to the particle: J_c = 4π R_p D_g (c_∞ − c_s). Positive for net absorption (c_∞ > c_s), negative for net evaporation (c_s > c_∞), zero at equilibrium.",
                    "expression": {
                        "op": "*",
                        "args": [
                            12.566370614359172,
                            "R_p",
                            "D_g",
                            {"op": "-", "args": ["c_inf", "c_s"]}
                        ]
                    }
                }
            },
            "equations": [],
            "tests": [
                {
                    "id": "default_conditions",
                    "description": "Default parameters: R_p=0.1 µm, D_g=2×10⁻⁵ m²/s, c_inf=10⁻⁶ mol/m³, c_s=0. J_c = 4π × 10⁻⁷ × 2×10⁻⁵ × 10⁻⁶ = 8π × 10⁻¹⁸ ≈ 2.513×10⁻¹⁷ mol/s. Anchors the basic absorption case at the declared defaults.",
                    "time_span": {"start": 0.0, "end": 1.0},
                    "assertions": [
                        {"variable": "J_c", "time": 0.0, "expected": 2.5132741228718345e-17, "tolerance": {"rel": 1e-12}}
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "larger_particle",
                    "description": "Particle radius R_p = 1 µm = 10⁻⁶ m (10× the default). J_c scales linearly with R_p, so the flux rises by 10× to ≈2.513×10⁻¹⁶ mol/s. Exercises the R_p wiring and confirms linear scaling.",
                    "time_span": {"start": 0.0, "end": 1.0},
                    "parameter_overrides": {"R_p": 1.0e-6},
                    "assertions": [
                        {"variable": "J_c", "time": 0.0, "expected": 2.5132741228718343e-16, "tolerance": {"rel": 1e-12}}
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "nonzero_surface_concentration",
                    "description": "Surface concentration c_s = 5×10⁻⁷ mol/m³ (half the bulk), c_inf = 10⁻⁶. The driving gradient Δc = 5×10⁻⁷ halves the default Δc = 10⁻⁶, so J_c drops to half its default value ≈ 1.257×10⁻¹⁷ mol/s. Exercises the (c_inf − c_s) concentration-gradient wiring.",
                    "time_span": {"start": 0.0, "end": 1.0},
                    "parameter_overrides": {"c_s": 5.0e-7},
                    "assertions": [
                        {"variable": "J_c", "time": 0.0, "expected": 1.2566370614359173e-17, "tolerance": {"rel": 1e-12}}
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "equilibrium_zero_flux",
                    "description": "Surface and bulk concentrations equal (c_inf = c_s = 10⁻⁶ mol/m³). The driving gradient vanishes and J_c = 0 exactly. Confirms that equilibrium produces exactly zero flux regardless of R_p, D_g.",
                    "time_span": {"start": 0.0, "end": 1.0},
                    "parameter_overrides": {"c_inf": 1.0e-6, "c_s": 1.0e-6},
                    "assertions": [
                        {"variable": "J_c", "time": 0.0, "expected": 0.0, "tolerance": {"abs": 1e-30}}
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "reverse_flux_evaporation",
                    "description": "Surface concentration c_s = 10⁻⁶ mol/m³ > c_inf = 0: the particle evaporates. J_c = 4π × 10⁻⁷ × 2×10⁻⁵ × (0 − 10⁻⁶) = −2.513×10⁻¹⁷ mol/s (same magnitude as default absorption, opposite sign). Confirms sign convention for net evaporation.",
                    "time_span": {"start": 0.0, "end": 1.0},
                    "parameter_overrides": {"c_inf": 0.0, "c_s": 1.0e-6},
                    "assertions": [
                        {"variable": "J_c", "time": 0.0, "expected": -2.5132741228718345e-17, "tolerance": {"rel": 1e-12}}
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "higher_diffusivity",
                    "description": "Gas-phase diffusivity D_g = 4×10⁻⁵ m²/s (2× the default). J_c scales linearly with D_g, so the flux doubles to ≈ 5.027×10⁻¹⁷ mol/s. Exercises the D_g wiring and confirms linear scaling.",
                    "time_span": {"start": 0.0, "end": 1.0},
                    "parameter_overrides": {"D_g": 4.0e-5},
                    "assertions": [
                        {"variable": "J_c", "time": 0.0, "expected": 5.026548245743669e-17, "tolerance": {"rel": 1e-12}}
                    ]
                }
            ],
            "examples": [
                {
                    "id": "flux_vs_particle_radius",
                    "description": "Sweep particle radius R_p from 1 nm to 10 µm log-spaced at default atmospheric conditions (D_g=2×10⁻⁵ m²/s, c_inf=10⁻⁶ mol/m³, c_s=0). J_c ∝ R_p: the absorption flux grows linearly with particle size, so larger particles in the continuum regime absorb gas at a proportionally higher molar rate.",
                    "initial_state": {"type": "per_variable", "values": {}},
                    "parameters": {},
                    "time_span": {"start": 0.0, "end": 1.0},
                    "parameter_sweep": {
                        "type": "cartesian",
                        "dimensions": [
                            {
                                "parameter": "R_p",
                                "range": {"start": 1.0e-9, "stop": 1.0e-5, "count": 51, "scale": "log"}
                            }
                        ]
                    },
                    "plots": [
                        {
                            "id": "Jc_vs_Rp",
                            "type": "line",
                            "description": "Continuum-regime molar flux J_c as a function of particle radius R_p. Linear on a log-log plot with slope 1, confirming J_c ∝ R_p.",
                            "x": {"variable": "R_p", "label": "Particle radius R_p (m)"},
                            "y": {"variable": "J_c", "label": "Molar flux J_c (mol/s)"}
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "flux_vs_concentration_gradient",
                    "description": "Sweep bulk concentration c_inf from 0 to 10⁻⁵ mol/m³ at c_s = 0. J_c grows linearly with c_inf, illustrating that the driving force for mass transfer is the concentration difference (c_∞ − c_s).",
                    "initial_state": {"type": "per_variable", "values": {}},
                    "parameters": {"c_s": 0.0},
                    "time_span": {"start": 0.0, "end": 1.0},
                    "parameter_sweep": {
                        "type": "cartesian",
                        "dimensions": [
                            {
                                "parameter": "c_inf",
                                "range": {"start": 1.0e-8, "stop": 1.0e-5, "count": 51, "scale": "log"}
                            }
                        ]
                    },
                    "plots": [
                        {
                            "id": "Jc_vs_cinf",
                            "type": "line",
                            "description": "Continuum-regime molar flux J_c as a function of bulk concentration c_inf (c_s = 0). Linear on a log-log plot with slope 1, confirming J_c ∝ Δc.",
                            "x": {"variable": "c_inf", "label": "Bulk concentration c_inf (mol/m³)"},
                            "y": {"variable": "J_c", "label": "Molar flux J_c (mol/s)"}
                        }
                    ]
                }
            ]
        }
    }
}
